<dl id="n32056a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n32" href="#n32056a">N32 (VI.B.23)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n32all.htm#n32056a"> 56(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> perisianisation / of ourdough</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In this way Persian <font color="green">[and Arabic]</font> words came into current use, and, though <font color="green">[Urdu (or conversational Hindostani)]</font> remained Indo-Aryan in its grammar and essential characteristics, it soon became unintelligible to any one who had not at least a moderate acquaintance with the language of Iran. This extreme <mark>Persianization of Urdu</mark> was due rather to Hindu than to Persian influence. <small> &ldquo;HINDOSTANI&rdquo; <a name="EBHI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBHI"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 479(b) [Hindostani as a Lingua Franca]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
